  <documentation>

    ##################################################################################
    General Notes
    ##################################################################################
    Control-Control only works on Composer 2.5.0 and newer software releases.
    Programming Actions and Events only works on Composer 2.5.1 and newer software releases.
    HTBaseT Receivers are hot to the touch when in use.  This is normal.




    ##################################################################################
    Setup
    ##################################################################################
    * Be sure that the switch and HDBaseT Receivers are powered off while making physical connections.
    * Do not run Cat5e / Cat6 cabling in close parallel proximity with high voltage wiring.
    * HDMI out 7 is shared with HDBaseT Out 7.  Only one will be active.  Both of these connections show up as HDMI out 7 in Composer.
    * HDMI out 8 is shared with HDBaseT Out 8.  Only one will be active.  Both of these connections show up as HDMI out 8 in Composer.
    * ONLY use High Speed Category 2 HDMI cables.  Cables with ferrites are not recommended.  Ferrites have caused problems with intermittent blanking and random pixel discoloration artifacts in the video.
    * HDMI cables with Redmere technology are NOT compatible with the HDMI Switch or HDBaseT Receiver.
    * 100 meters is the maximum recommended length for Cat5e / Cat6.
    * It is strongly recommended to not use patch panels, wall plates, or any other interruption of the Cat5e / Cat6 cable.  For the best possible performance use one run of continuous cable from the switch to the HDBaseT receiver with an RJ45 on each end.

    ##################################################
    Calibration
    ##################################################
    The HDMI switch has EDID management.  The way this works is through calibration.  There is a button under the Actions tab in the driver to calibrate and reset the calibration.  To calibrate all source devices should be on and all displays should be on and set to the correct input.  When the calibrate button is hit the switch will go through every device and get all the EDID information from it.  From this data a new EDID will be created with the settings which ensure all devices can display the video and playback the audio.  This new EDID is given to all source devices so when new zones join a zone in progress there is no interruption. 

    This results in the lowest common settings for video and audio.  This means that if there is a mix of 3D and regular 2D TV’s all displays will be 2D unless a Zone Lock is acquired.  Similarly if there is a mix of various surround sound capabilities and stereo sound, stereo will always be used unless a Zone Lock is acquired.

    Locking a zone means that a zone gets exclusive access to a source.  When this happens the zone’s real EDID is passed to the source and the full capabilities of the zone are then enabled.  So if a zone is 3D with surround sound in a system where other zones are 2D and stereo, the zone with the lock will get 3D and surround sound.  When a zone has a lock on a source, that source is no longer available to any other zones in the system.  When a zone tries to acquire a source which has been locked a programming event is fired which should be handled.




    ##################################################
    HDMI Switch
    ##################################################


    #################################
    IP Port
    #################################
    This port is how the Control4 system will control the switch.  This should simply be connected to your network.


    #################################
    HDMI Input
    #################################
    Connect your sources physically and make the binding connections in Composer.

    *NOTE : Always use proper cable management to provide strain relief on the HDMI cables.  Due to the size and weight of HDMI cables they can pull down and become disconnected over time.  Always make connections in a way which provides a straight in connection and prevents movement of the cable.  The use of cable management systems and zip ties is strongly recommended.
    *NOTE : When installed in a rack a lacer bar should be placed behind the switch level with the HDMI connectors.  All HDMI cables should be secured to this lacer to prevent cable movement or pull on the connectors.


    #################################
    IR
    #################################
    Each IR input is connected to its respective HDBaseT output.  Meaning IR 1 is connected to HDBaseT Receiver 1.  The IR can be directed from the switch to the HDBaseT Receiver (default) or from the HDBaseT Receiver to the switch.  This is configurable on the properties page in Composer.  

    When in Switch-to-Receiver mode the input should be connected to the IR output of a Control4 Controller.  Make all bindings from the controller to the end devices as the switch and HDBaseT Receiver are transparent to the system.  Connect an IR bud or blaster to the HDBaseT Receiver.

    When in Receiver-to-Switch mode the input to the HDBaseT Receiver must be an IR Receiver.  Connecting directly to a Control4 controller will not work.  Then connect the IR bud or blaster to the switch.

    *NOTE : Only 38kHz frequency devices are supported.
    *NOTE : When creating the bindings in composer bind the output of the controller directly to the device connected on the HDBaseT Receiver.
    *NOTE : When connecting a Control4 Controller (for Switch-to-Receiver mode) IR port a 3 connector (stereo) mini-jack connector must be used.
    *NOTE : When connecting an IR emitter (for Receiver-to-Switch mode) a Control4 2 connector (mono) mini-jack connector must be used.

    #################################
    RS232
    #################################
    The RS232 ports are also connected one to one to the respective HDBaseT Receivers.  Connect directly to a Control4 controller with a stereo mini-jack to mini-jack cable if applicable, or use a DB-9 to mini-jack stereo cable.  Make all bindings from the controller to the end device as the switch and HDBaseT Receiver are transparent to the system.  Connect the HDBaseT Receiver to device using a DB-9 to mini-jack stereo cable.

    *NOTE : Depending on the device being controlled you may need a NULL MODEM adapter.
    *NOTE : When creating the bindings in Composer Pro, bind the output of the controller directly to the device connected on the HDBaseT Receiver.


    #################################
    LAN Ports
    #################################
    The LAN Ports on the switch are connected one to one to the respective baluns.  Connect the switch LAN Port to a network switch to provide network connections on the balun.


    #################################
    Audio Outs
    #################################
    This switch has analog stereo audio outputs.  These are switched separate from the HDMI outputs.  There are 8 total audio outputs to allow distribution of any source throughout the audio distribution of the home.  For greater control and distribution connect these analog audio outputs to a Control4 Audio Matrix Switch and/or a Control4 4/8 Zone Matrix Amplifier.

    *NOTE : If the source is multi-channel audio the analog audio output will be muted.


    #################################
    HDBaseT and HDMI Output
    #################################
    Connect HDBaseT outputs to HDBaseT Receivers over Cat5e / Cat6 cable.  Cat6 is recommended.  Connect HDMI outputs to HDMI inputs if applicable.  Connect bindings in composer to HDMI out in the driver.  100 meters is the maximum supported cable length and has been tested on Cat6 and Cat5e.

    *NOTE : Termination of Cat5e / Cat6 cables is extremely important.  Make sure your terminations are good.
    *NOTE : Because of the different usage of wires in the Cat5e / Cat6 cable and the greater bandwidth requirements for HDBaseT you may get a successful network connection using a cable but the HDBaseT may not work.  Test terminations and cable.
    *NOTE : HDMI Output : Always use proper cable management to provide strain relief on the HDMI cables.  Due to the size and weight of HDMI cables they can pull down and become disconnected over time.  Always make connections in a way which provides a straight in connection and prevents movement of the cable.  The use of cable management systems and zip ties is strongly recommended.


    ##################################################
    HDBaseT Receivers
    ##################################################

    #################################
    HDMI Output
    #################################
    Connect the HDMI output from the HDBaseT Receiver  to the display device or receiver.  It is NOT recommended or supported to connect this to another video switch.

    *NOTE : Always use proper cable management to provide strain relief on the HDMI cables.  Due to the size and weight of HDMI cables they can pull down and become disconnected over time.  Always make connections in a way which provides a straight in connection and prevents movement of the cable.  The use of cable management systems and zip ties is strongly recommended.


    #################################
    IR
    #################################
    When in Switch-to-Receiver mode, connect an IR bud or blaster to the IR port on the HDBaseT Receiver. When in Receiver-to-Switch mode, connect an IR sensor to this port on the HDBaseT Receiver.

    *NOTE : A Control4 Controller can not be connected to this port to send IR back to the switch.
    *NOTE : When connecting an IR emitter (for Receiver-to-Switch mode) a Control4 emitter must be used.
    *NOTE : When connecting an IR sensor to this port a 3 conductor (stereo) mini jack must be used.

    #################################
    RS232
    #################################
    Connect to the device to be controlled using a stereo mini-jack to DB-9 cable.

    *NOTE : Depending on the device being controlled you may need a NULL MODEM adapter.
    *NOTE : Depending on the device being controlled you may need a gender changer adapter.


    #################################
    LAN Port
    #################################
    If the corresponding LAN Port connection on the HDMI switch is connected to the network this port can be connected to any network device.


    ##################################################################################
    Driver
    ##################################################################################
    This section documents the driver itself, settings, etc.


    ##################################################
    Properties
    ##################################################
    The driver version section has just one property, the version of this driver.

    The power section has two properties.  The first is the power status.  The device's power status can be Unknown, Standby, or Powered On.  The second is Connected To Network.  This property indicates the device is online and we are communicating with it.

    The calibration section simply indicates the state of calibration.  Either NOT Calibrated, Calibrating, or Calibrated.  See more on calibration below.

    The firmware section has properties related to the firmware.  This includes the version on the device, the version on the server (for upgrade), the URL for the firmware on the server, the firmware upgrade mode (automatic or manual), and the status of the last upgrade (if applicable).  The default URL is: http://update.control4.com/release2/firmware/c4_8x8_hdmivswitch/c4_8x8_hdmivswitch_fw.nxp

    The Lock Settings section has a property to prevent any source stealing.  When set to true, if any zone attempts a lock while another zone is viewing the same source, this lock will fail, this includes when auto lock is set to true.  A programming event will fire in this case for customization by the installer.  The remaining properties in this section, one for each source, is to prevent a lock on that source.  This is used if there is a source which the installer or homeowner wants to always be available in all zones.

    The Audio Delay section indicates the state of the delay for each respective analog audio source.  The range is 0-255 and each increment is equal to 32 audio samples.  \nAt a sample rate of 32 kHz a value of 255 is 255 mS.  \nAt a sample rate of 44.1 kHz a value of 255 is 180 mS.

    The IR Direction section lets you choose which direction the IR goes.  You can send IR signals from the switch to the HDBaseT Receiver, or you can send IR from the receiver to the switch.  The use case for each is as follows: you can control a device, such as a TV on the HDBaseT Receiver side by connecting the switch's IR port to a Control4 controller.  If you want to control something near the switch from the location of the HDBaseT Receiver, you can change this direction and use an IR capture device connected to the HDBaseT Receiver and an emitter connected to the switch.

    The Auto Zone Lock section allows any specified zone to always attempt to lock the requested source so that full capabilities (such as surround sound, 3D, etc.) can be utilized at the zone.  If a zone auto locks every source it selects will be locked to the zone without the additional need of programming.  If the source is already locked to a zone it can not be locked again, so use of the auto zone lock should be done with caution.  The primary use case is a dedicated theatre where you always want full capabilities.  If the prevent source stealing property is set to true and another zone is viewing the source, the zone lock will fail.


    ##################################################
    Actions
    ##################################################
    There are the following actions available in this driver.
    Print Output To Input Mapping        : This action will print in the lua output a textual representation of the current active zone to source bindings.  This is the same information as in the Control-Control but in textual form.
    Print Output To Locked Input Mapping : This action will print in the lua output a textual representation of the current active zone to locked source bindings.  Meaning if a zone has a lock on a source that mapping will be printed.
    Reset Calibration                    : This action will clear calibration on the switch.
    Calibrate                            : This action will tell the switch to perform a calibration, which will tell the switch to learn about all the devices connected to it.  This is how the switch can provide faster switching times and no blanking when zones join other active zones by selecting the same source.
    Upgrade Firmware                     : This action will tell the switch to perform a firmware upgrade.  If there is no upgrade available this will result in no action.

    ##################################################
    Programming
    ##################################################
    There are the following programming events for this driver.  \nThe first is when the zone to source binding changes.  \nThe second (set of programming events) is for when a zone attempts to select a source and the source is already locked in a zone.  There is one event for each zone.  \nThe next (set of programming events) is for when multiple zones are viewing the same source and one zone locks the source.  This results in the non locked zones "losing" the source.  In this case there is an event for each zone which "loses" its source.  \nThe next group of programming events (one for each zone) is when a lock fails because the flag has been set to prevent sources from being turned off in other zones.

    There are two available programming actions for this driver.  One is to programmatically select a source in a zone and the other is for zone locking.  The first is straightforward and allows the ability to automatically select any source for any zone.  The second is for when auto locking is not appropriate and allows full control to be placed in the hands of either the integrator or the end user.  Based on any action a zone can lock any given source.

    *NOTE : Be mindful not to create a programming loop.  For example, if on a source selection failure you select a source automatically, if that source is a locked source you could end up trying to select, fail, programming event, trying to select, fail programming event, ...


    ##################################################################################
    Configuration
    ##################################################################################

    #################################
    Network
    #################################
    This switch supports DHCP and Static IP.  To set the Static IP use System Manager to connect to the device.  System Manager will open a web browser to the configuration URL on the device.  Static IP settings can be entered on the web page.

    *NOTE : You MUST hit enter on each field after you input the text.


    #################################
    Calibration
    #################################
    This process gathers all of the information from all the devices connected.  This results in faster switching times and isolates the effect of one zone from another zone when new connections are routed.  To perform calibration manually power on ALL devices connected to the input and output of the switch and set to the appropriate inputs.  Next press the "Calibrate" button on the Actions tab of the driver.  This process may take several minutes depending on the number of devices connected.  There is a property for the status of calibration on the properties tab of the driver which will indicate if the device is calibrated or not, and if it is currently calibrating.

    If calibration is not performed the device will learn each source and zone over time and the normal HDMI switching delay will be seen each time a new zone or source is learned.  When the switch reboots or loses power this learn over time process will happen again as the learning is only saved during calibration.  For the best experience always perform calibration.


    #################################
    Audio Outs
    #################################
    This device supports a delay for the analog audio output ports.  The delay is the value entered in the properties page * 32 samples.  Thus the actual delay is dependant upon the sample rate of the audio being played.  To configure the delay setup a video session to the zone you are configuring.  Listen to the audio which is on the HDMI and listen to the analog audio at the same time.  Adjust the audio delay if necessary.  This delay is tied to the source device so any output which gets mapped to a source will get that source's audio delay.


    #################################
    Zone Locking
    #################################
    A source can be locked to a specific zone.  This allows all the capabilities of a specific zone to be used. Without locking the zone would be limited to the capabilities of the least capable zone in the system.

    For example, your theatre may have 3D capabilities when no other zone in your system does.  Without a zone lock your theatre will not have 3D capabilities.  When you lock the zone the zone gets exclusive access to the source and the source can then provide all the features available for that zone.  When a zone locks a source that source is not available to the other zones in the system until the zone with the lock turns off or selects another source.  During this time the Control4 system still allows other zones to select the source but the switch will only display a blank (black) screen.  Also worthy of noting is that in this state the Control4 system believes the zone with the blank screen is controlling the source device and control commands will be sent to the device.

    When zone locking the first zone to lock a source will get the lock and keep the lock until it switches sources or is turned off.  If another zone attempts to lock the same source it will fail to lock and a blank screen will be displayed.

    There are two ways to acquire a zone lock.  
    * The first is an auto lock feature.  Any zone can be an auto locking zone.  This means any source it selects will automatically be locked.  Having multiple auto locking zones is possible but caution should be used as too many auto locking zones will likely lead to an inability to share sources.  In some cases it may be desired that no sources are ever shared and in this case the auto locking feature could be enabled for all zones.  The typical use case is for a theatre to lock the source so that 3D and surround sound will be enabled.
    * The second way to lock a zone is through programming.  In the Actions pane in the programming section of composer programming can be created for any zone to lock whatever its current source is.  The event to initiate this programming is then up to the installer.

    *NOTE : If multiple zones have the same source selected a lock will turn off the video in the other zones.
    *NOTE : To see what zones have locks use the button in the Actions tab of the properties for the driver.    



    ##################################################################################
    Troubleshooting
    ##################################################################################
    * Double check all connections are fully engaged and that cables are not sagging or pulling out of their connectors.
    * Make sure your HDMI cables are category 2 high speed and do not have ferrites.
    * Have a known good and tested 100 meter length of Cat6 with RJ45 on each end for testing.  This should allow a process of elimination to prove the equipment is working and the structured wiring is the problem.
    * Test all Cat5e / Cat6 cables and terminations with a cable tester.  Even if this test passes, and no other problem can be determined, reterminating may solve problems.  It is known that ethernet network can work just fine and HDBaseT can not work on the same cable and terminations.
    * If you do not get video and audio try connecting the source directly to the display.  If this does not work there is likely a problem with the TV being unable to accept HDCP from the source device.
    * If you do not get video and audio route a Control4 controller through the switch to the display.  The Control4 controllers do not do HDCP and only output 720p.  This is your best chance for success when diagnosing and troubleshooting.


    #################################
    Encountered Issues and Corrections
    #################################
    * Small white pixels throughout the screen.  Commonly called snow or noise.
    ** Ferrites on the HDMI cable were causing this.  Replacing the cable corrected the problem.

    * Source does not display on any zone, no signal
    ** Double check the connections between the source and the switch are secure, not flexed, and proper cable management has been implemented to provide strain relief.

    * Source does not display on any zone, tv does display a black screen
    ** Reboot the source device.  If a source device stops displaying video it may need to be rebooted.  Also check for firmware upgrades for the source device.

    * The first time I join a zone to a different zone already playing the original zone blanks for a moment then continues on.
    ** This indicates the switch has not been calibrated properly.  See calibration section above more more details.

    * I don't get any audio out of my TV in one zone but it works fine in another zone.
    * I don't get any audio out of the analog audio outputs on the switch.
    ** Verify that the source device is playing stereo audio.  If the source device is providing any kind of surround sound it may play back on a receiver or a television which can decode surround, but will not play back on a television which only accepts 2 channel stereo audio.
    *** Example: Netflix audio works in my theatre, but not my living room.
    *** Fix    : Change audio settings for the program you’re watching to stereo.

    * I don't get any video out of my TV in one zone, but it works fine in another zone.
    ** Verify the source device is displaying in something that this particular TV can display.  Some devices can be forced into a particular output mode which your TV does not display, and the display device may not honor EDID.
    *** Example: I can get no video when I select my cable or satellite box
    *** Fix    : The cable box was placed into 1080p mode, and the TV only display's 1080i.  Change the output settings on the device and it will begin working.

  </documentation>
